{{nihongo foot|'''''The Wing of Madoola'''''|マドゥーラの翼|Madūra no Tsubasa|lit. "Wings of Madoola"|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 1986 [[Action game|action]]-[[Platform game|platform]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Sunsoft]] for the [[Family Computer]]. It stars Lucia, a magic-wielding warrior of the Rameru clan. Darutos, a descendant of the Rameru line, found the Wing of Madoola statue and used it to build a demonic fortress and summon demons to conquer the world. Lucia must retrieve the statue and stop Darutos. Throughout the journey, the player explores and search for [[Item (gaming)|item]]s and [[power-up]]s to increase Lucia's attributes, while fighting enemies and defeating [[Boss (video gaming)|bosses]].

''The Wing of Madoola'' was designed by Kenji Sada, being his first project at Sunsoft after joining the company in 1986, and developed over the course of six months. Sada acted as the game's main programmer, planner, and team lead. He intended to make an action game and choose a female lead for the game, a decision he felt gave character to the title. Artist Kenji "Moriken" Mori acted as character designer. The music was composed by Naoki Kodaka, with assistance by sound programmer Naohisa Morota.

''The Wing of Madoola'' garnered mixed reception from critics and retrospective commentarists. The game was supplemented with [[manga]] adaptations and music albums. The character of Lucia would make appearances in other titles, including a [[doujinshi]] [[adventure game]] released for [[Personal computer|PC]] in 2009, and became a popular [[Sunsoft]] character among Japanese retro gaming fans.

== Gameplay and premise ==
[[File:FC The Wing of Madoola.png|frame|left|Lucia fighting against enemies in stage 2]]
''The Wing of Madoola'' is a side-scrolling [[Action game|action]]-[[Platform game|platform]] game with  [[Role-playing video game|role-playing]] elements, similar to ''[[Athena (video game)|Athena]]'' (1986).<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name=":0"/><ref name="PGoNF">{{cite book|chapter=マドゥーラの翼|title=懐かしファミコンパーフェクトガイド|volume=1|series=Perfect Guide|publisher=Magazine Box|date=April 21, 2016|page=41|language=ja|isbn=978-4906735891}}</ref> The story is set in the kingdom of Badham, which hosted a bird statue known as the Wing of Madoola. The wing grants power to rule the world to the one who possessed it, which caused many wars between nations to have control over it. A king hid it to stop the wars and entrusted the Rameru family to protect the wing. Darutos, a descendant of the Rameru lineage, found the statue and betrayed his family by using it to build a demonic fortress and summon demons to conquer the world. Lucia, a magic-wielding warrior of the Rameru clan, must retrieve the statue and stop Darutos.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum">{{cite book|title=マドゥーラの翼|date=December 1986|publisher=[[Sunsoft]]|type=取扱説明書}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{cite news|last=Romano|first=Sal|url=https://www.gematsu.com/2024/04/sunsoft-is-back-retro-game-selection-launches-april-18-in-japan-for-switch-pc|title=SUNSOFT is Back! Retro Game Selection launches April 18 in Japan for Switch, PC|work=Gematsu|date=April 10, 2024|access-date=2024-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240411023056/https://www.gematsu.com/2024/04/sunsoft-is-back-retro-game-selection-launches-april-18-in-japan-for-switch-pc|archive-date=2024-04-11|url-status=live}}</ref>

The player controls Lucia and fights against enemies across 16 stages.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/> The main objective of each stage is to locate and defeat a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]], and collect a crystal ball under their possession in order to gain entrance to the next stage.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/><ref name="FCMv2i20">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/family-computer-magazine-issue-25-december-19th-1986/Family%20Computer%20Magazine%20-%20Issue%2025%20-%20December%2019th%201986%20%28Compressed%29/page/84/mode/2up|title=マドゥーラの翼|magazine={{ill|Family Computer Magazine|lt=Family Computer Magazine|ja|ファミリーコンピュータMagazine}}|volume=2|issue=20|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=December 19, 1986|pages=84–87|language=ja}}</ref> Lucia can jump, climb ladders, crouch, attack with her sword, and use magic. The player explores and searches for [[Item (gaming)|item]]s and [[power-up]]s to increase Lucia's maximum [[Health (game terminology)|health]] and attributes.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/><ref name="FCMv2i20"/><ref name="FHH13">{{cite magazine |date=December 19, 1986 |title=New Soft: マドゥーラの翼 |url=https://archive.org/details/no.-013-1986-12-19/page/n101/mode/2up |magazine={{ill|Famicom Hisshō Hon|lt=Famicom Hisshō Hon|ja|ファミコン必勝本}} |language=ja |publisher=[[Takarajimasha]] |issue=13 |pages=98–99}}</ref> These items and power-ups include boots which augment her overall speed and jumping abilities, swords to increase attack strength, health jars, and spell books.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/><ref name="FCMv2i20"/> There are six types of magical attacks, ranging from flame swords to flash magic.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/><ref name="FCMv2i20"/><ref name="FHH13"/>

The game is considered difficult to beat.<ref name="PGoNF"/> Enemies inflict large amounts of damage, and many continue to attack Lucia with multiple consecutive hits. Enemies can also withstand a tremendous amount of damage before being defeated. Later stages become more maze-like, making the player overlook necessary items that can make the completion of the game much easier.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/> The [[Game over|game is over]] if Lucia's health is depleted.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="TWoMum"/>

== Development ==
''The Wing of Madoola'' was designed by Kenji Sada, who had previously worked at [[T&E Soft]] on a [[educational game]] for the [[Family Computer]] titled ''[[Keisan Game]]''.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|last=Gancer|first=Stefan|url=https://www.gamingalexandria.com/wp/2018/12/06/the-making-of-the-wing-of-madoola/|title=The Making of The Wing of Madoola|work=Gaming Alexandria|date=December 6, 2018|access-date=2023-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014113607/https://www.gamingalexandria.com/wp/2018/12/06/the-making-of-the-wing-of-madoola/|archive-date=2019-10-14|url-status=live}}<br/>{{cite book|last=Gancer|first=Stefan|title=The History of Sunsoft|volume=1|publisher=[[Limited Run Games]]|date=March 17, 2023|pages=1–224|isbn=978-1955183178}}</ref> It was Sada's first project at [[Sunsoft]], who joined the company in 1986 after being invited by his former high school friend Kenji Kajita. Sada acted as the game's main programmer, planner, and team lead. Kajita served as co-programmer, with Atsushi Sakai and a programmer named Nakagawa providing additional support. Kazuyuki Sugiura, who worked on the Famicom port of ''[[Fantasy Zone]]'', and "Kiritan" Simomura were responsible for the map design and graphics respectively.<ref name=":0"/><ref name="SoM">{{cite web|last=M.|first=Nathan|url=https://www.infochunk.com/madoola/conversation.html|title=Conversation with Kenji Sada|work=Secrets of Madoola|date=March 18, 2023|access-date=2023-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230321234719/https://www.infochunk.com/madoola/conversation.html|archive-date=2023-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> Sugiura initially joined Sunsoft as a part-timer, but eventually became a full-time employee.<ref name="Friday">{{cite web|last=Yokohama|first=Daisuke|url=https://en.friday.news/article/10725?page=2|title=Legendary game company "Sun Electronics" NES developers "Laughing Roundtable"...!|work=[[Friday (magazine)|Friday]]|publisher=[[Kodansha]]|date=September 22, 2022|pages=1–3|access-date=2023-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815024608/https://en.friday.news/article/10725?page=2|archive-date=2023-08-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Artist Kenji "Moriken" Mori, who had previously worked on ''[[Tōkaidō Gojūsan-tsugi (video game)|Tōkaidō Gojūsan-tsugi]]'' and ''[[Dead Zone (video game)|Dead Zone]]'' (1986), acted as the game's character designer.<ref name=":0"/><ref name="MsCafe">{{cite web|last=Mori|first=Kenji|url=http://moriken.kalin.to/about/about.htm|title=もりけんプロフィール|work=M's CAFE|date=2009|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091211192544/http://moriken.kalin.to/about/about.htm|archive-date=2009-12-11|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="TGMSSoS">{{cite AV media|date=January 29, 2010|title=ザ・ゲームメーカー ~ サンソフト編|trans-title=The Game Maker: Sunsoft ~ The Spirit of Sunsoft|medium=[[DVD]]|series=[[GameCenter CX]]|language=ja|location=Japan|publisher=[[Fuji Television]], Gascoin Company}} ([https://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/sp_Sunsoft-Interview.html Transcription] by Chris Covell. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211108010026/https://www.chrismcovell.com/secret/sp_Sunsoft-Interview.html|date=2021--11-08}}. [https://www.glitterberri.com/developer-interviews/the-spirit-of-sunsoft/ Translation] by GlitterBerri's Game Translations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211104033600/https://www.glitterberri.com/developer-interviews/the-spirit-of-sunsoft/|date=2021-11-04}}).</ref><ref name="ACTGvB">{{cite magazine|title=わが青春のサンソフト: 『マドゥーラの翼』|magazine=Action Gameside|volume=B|publisher=Micro Magazine|date=March 7, 2013|pages=90–93|language=ja|isbn=978-4896374162}}</ref> The music was composed by [[Naoki Kodaka]], with  assistance by sound programmer Naohisa Morota.<ref name=":0"/><ref name="SoM"/><ref name="VGMdb4"/><ref name="ROMCDiSun">{{cite book|author=Clarice Disc|chapter=LINER NOTES: 小高 直樹|title=Rom Cassette Disc In SUNSOFT|publisher=[[City Connection (company)|City Connection]]|date=June 29, 2011}} ([https://shmuplations.com/sunsoftmusic/ Translation] by Shmuplations. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911055445/https://shmuplations.com/sunsoftmusic/|date=2014-09-11}}).</ref>

''The Wing of Madoola'' was developed over the course of six months.<ref name="SoM"/> Sada intended to make an action game instead of a [[action role-playing game]]. Sada choose a female lead for the game, stating that the game would have been very similar to ''[[Dragon Buster]]'' if the protagoinist was a male. Sada did not have a specific reason for choosing making a woman the protagonist, but felt the decision gave the game character.<ref name=":0"/> Sugiura conceived the game's title, though he explained the name had no meaning and jokingly explained that "I was just doodling because I liked the balance of the characters."<ref name=":0"/><ref name="Friday"/>

== Release ==
''The Wing of Madoola'' was first announced on October 17, 1986, in that week's issue of ''[[Famitsu]]'', planning for a November release date.<ref name="Fam9">{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:Famitsu_JP_0009.pdf&page=78|title=New Soft: マドゥーラの翼|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=9|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=October 17, 1986|page=76|access-date=2023-08-22|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230814003029/https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:Famitsu_JP_0009.pdf&page=78|archive-date=2023-08-14|url-status=live}}</ref> It was published in Japan by [[Sunsoft]] for the [[Family Computer]] on December 18, 1986.<ref name="FamTWoM"/><ref name="ACTGvB"/><ref name="FCMv2i19">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/details/family-computer-magazine-issue-24-december-5th-1986/Family%20Computer%20Magazine%20-%20Issue%2024%20-%20December%205th%201986%20%28Compressed%29/page/90/mode/1up|title=超新作ゲーム先取つ大作戦 62本 - マドゥーラの翼|magazine={{ill|Family Computer Magazine|lt=Family Computer Magazine|ja|ファミリーコンピュータMagazine}}|volume=2|issue=19|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=December 5, 1986|page=90|language=ja}}</ref> Plans for a North American localization never materialized; Sunsoft of America's Richard Robbins criticized the game harshly, saying that action games like ''[[Contra (video game)|Contra]]'' sell in North America and that female protagonists were not worth talking about.<ref name="SoM"/> An [[Arcade game|arcade]] version dubbed ''VS. The Wings of Madoola''{{efn|{{nihongo|VS. マドゥーラの翼|VS. Madūra no Tsubasa}}}} was planned for the [[Nintendo VS. System]], an arcade system based on the Famicom hardware.<ref name=":0"/><ref name="FF">{{cite web|url=https://www.flyerfever.com/vs-lionex-and-vs-madura-no-tsubasa/|title=Vs. Lionex / Vs. Madura no Tsubasa|website=Flyer Fever|date=February 20, 2021|access-date=2023-08-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230602055437/https://www.flyerfever.com/vs-lionex-and-vs-madura-no-tsubasa/|archive-date=2023-06-02|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="TEb">{{cite web|last=Yarwood|first=Jack|url=https://www.timeextension.com/news/2023/08/sunsoft-shares-image-of-unreleased-wings-of-madoola-vs-system-prototype|title=Sunsoft Shares Image Of Unreleased Wings Of Madoola VS. System Prototype|work=[[Time Extension]]|publisher=[[Hookshot Media]]|date=August 11, 2023|access-date=2023-07-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230811141511/https://www.timeextension.com/news/2023/08/sunsoft-shares-image-of-unreleased-wings-of-madoola-vs-system-prototype|archive-date=2023-08-11|url-status=live}}</ref> Developed by Kenji Sada, it introduced changes that adapted the game for the arcade format, such as a health counter which slowly runs down.<ref name="SoM"/><ref name="GamingHelltwom">{{cite web|last=Cooke|first=Ant|url=https://www.gaminghell.co.uk/TheWingOfMadoola.html|title=The Wing of Madoola - After years of battle, the land was always in the state of chaos|work=Gaming Hell|date=May 1, 2020|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200501163641/https://www.gaminghell.co.uk/TheWingOfMadoola.html|archive-date=2020-05-01|url-status=live}}</ref> The VS. edition was shelved after its location test did not go well, although a prototype was discovered by Sunsoft in 2023.<ref name="SoM"/><ref name="TEb"/> The game was first re-released alongside ''[[Super Arabian]]'' and ''[[Atlantis no Nazo]]'' as a part of the ''Ultra2000 Sunsoft Classic Games Vol. 1'' compilation, published by MediaKite for [[Microsoft Windows]] on June 29, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.4gamer.net/news/history/2001.06/20010605201332detail.html|title=ファミコンのソフトがWindows版で登場！|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=June 5, 2001|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020311104635/http://www.4gamer.net/news/history/2001.06/20010605201332detail.html|archive-date=2002-03-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0106/08/news05.html|title=「いっき」などサンソフトタイトルがPCに蘇る|work=[[SoftBank Group|SoftBank Games]]|publisher={{ill|ITmedia|lt=ITmedia|ja|ITmedia}}|date=June 8, 2001|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221120081932/https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/gsnews/0106/08/news05.html|archive-date=2022-11-20|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also included alongside ''[[Tōkaidō Gojūsan-tsugi (video game)|Tōkaidō Gojūsan-tsugi]]'' as part of ''Memorial Series Sunsoft Vol. 3'', a double-pack published by Sunsoft for [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] on December 27, 2001.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/slps03366.html|title=メモリアル☆シリーズ サンソフトVOL.3|work=PlayStation Official Site Software Catalog|publisher=[[Sony Interactive Entertainment]]|date=2016|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408053838/https://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/slps03366.html|archive-date=2016-04-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>

The game was re-bundled along with ''Super Arabian'' and ''Atlantis no Nazo'' as part of ''Sunsoft Masterpiece Selection 1 Yū Yū'' compilation, published by MediaKite for Windows on July 2, 2004.<ref name="Gamer">{{cite web|url=https://www.gamer.ne.jp/game/1000033263/|title=サンソフト傑作選1 遊遊のゲーム情報|work=Gamer|publisher=ixll Co., Ltd.|date=2023|access-date=2023-08-31|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230831231359/https://www.gamer.ne.jp/game/1000033263/|archive-date=2023-08-31|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/145011473|title=Windows95/98/Me/2000/XP CDソフト 遊遊シリーズ サンソフト傑作選1|website=Suruga-ya.jp|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230815005527/https://www.suruga-ya.jp/product/detail/145011473|archive-date=2023-08-15|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, the ''Memorial Series Sunsoft Vol. 3'' pack was made available by Sunsoft as part of the "Game Archives" line on [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0709/27/news097.html|title=「ゲームアーカイブス」9月発売タイトルを発表|work=ねとらぼ|publisher={{ill|ITmedia|lt=ITmedia|ja|ITmedia}}|date=September 27, 2007|access-date=2023-08-24|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230824004057/https://nlab.itmedia.co.jp/games/articles/0709/27/news097.html|archive-date=2023-08-24|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/jp0202npjj00085_000000000000000001.html|title=「ゲームアーカイブス」メモリアル☆シリーズ サンソフトVOL.3|work=PlayStation Official Site Software Catalog|publisher=[[Sony Interactive Entertainment]]|date=2021|access-date=2023-08-24|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210228044721/http://www.jp.playstation.com/software/title/jp0202npjj00085_000000000000000001.html|archive-date=2021-02-28|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2010, ''The Wing of Madoola'' was re-released in digital form for Windows through [[D4 Enterprise]]'s Project EGG service.<ref name="ACTGvB"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20100330004/|title=【リリース】「EGG」サンソフトのファミコンゲーム「いっき」など5作品配信|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=March 30, 2010|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100401082948/https://www.4gamer.net/games/008/G000896/20100330004/|archive-date=2010-04-01|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2013, it was re-released on the Japanese [[3DS Virtual Console]] via [[Nintendo eShop]].<ref name="ACTGvB"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2013/01/23/63175.html|title=愛と魔法と夢の大冒険『マドゥーラの翼』3DSバーチャルコンソールに登場|work={{ill|Inside Games|lt=Inside Games|ja|iNSIDE (ニュースサイト)}}|publisher={{ill|IID, Inc.|lt=IID, Inc.|ja|イード (企業)}}|date=January 23, 2013|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130126050301/https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2013/01/23/63175.html|archive-date=2013-01-26|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019, the company [[City Connection (company)|City Connection]] announced that the game will be included alongside several other Sunsoft titles as part of the third compilation in the ''Rom Cassette Collection'' series.<ref>{{cite news|last=Romano|first=Sal|url=https://www.gematsu.com/2019/08/city-connection-announces-rom-cassette-collection-series-including-jaleco-and-sun-corporation-collections|title=City Connection announces Rom Cassette Collection series, including Jaleco and Sun Corporation collections|work=Gematsu|date=August 21, 2019|access-date=2023-08-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821154946/https://www.gematsu.com/2019/08/city-connection-announces-rom-cassette-collection-series-including-jaleco-and-sun-corporation-collections|archive-date=2019-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2023, Sunsoft launched a crowdfunding campaign via the Japanese website Camp-Fire for [[Nintendo Switch]] and [[Personal computer|PC]] ports of the game, as well as ''Tōkaidō Gojūsan-tsugi'' and ''[[Ripple Island (video game)|Ripple Island]]''.<ref name="Gematsu">{{cite news|last=Romano|first=Sal|url=https://www.gematsu.com/2023/06/sunsoft-plans-crowdfunding-campaign-to-port-three-famicom-titles-to-switch-pc|title=SUNSOFT plans crowdfunding campaign to port three Famicom titles to Switch, PC|work=Gematsu|date=June 22, 2023|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230623222329/https://www.gematsu.com/2023/06/sunsoft-plans-crowdfunding-campaign-to-port-three-famicom-titles-to-switch-pc|archive-date=2023-06-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="TEa">{{cite web|last=Yarwood|first=Jack|url=https://www.timeextension.com/news/2023/06/sunsoft-wants-to-revive-three-more-classic-famicom-games-for-switch-and-pc|title=Sunsoft Wants To Revive Three More Classic Famicom Games For Switch & PC — And is using crowdfunding to make it happen!|work=[[Time Extension]]|publisher=[[Hookshot Media]]|date=June 23, 2023|access-date=2023-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230623150334/https://www.timeextension.com/news/2023/06/sunsoft-wants-to-revive-three-more-classic-famicom-games-for-switch-and-pc|archive-date=2023-06-23|url-status=live}}</ref> The campaign ended on August 31, 2023, raising ¥21.250.799 ($145.350,32) in total.<ref name="Gematsu"/><ref name="TEa"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Sugiura|first=Aono|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/650/G065049/20230901035/|title=「マドゥーラの翼」など3タイトルを現行機で復刻するクラファンが2125万799円の支援を受け成功。ライブ配信「SUNSOFT is back! 3」情報まとめ|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=September 1, 2023|access-date=2023-09-01|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230901213547/https://www.4gamer.net/games/650/G065049/20230901035/|archive-date=2023-09-01|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 18, 2024, the games were included as part of the ''Sunsoft Is Back! Retro Game Selection'' compilation for Switch and PC.<ref name=":1"/>

=== Other media ===
To promote the game's release, Sunsoft held a contest to find a hidden password within the game's eighth stage.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/> The players could send the password to Sunsoft in exchange for a cassette tape, which contained two arranged tracks from ''The Wing of Madoola'' and ''[[Dead Zone (video game)|Dead Zone]]'' (1986) respectively.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="VGMdb1">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/19610|title=The Wing of Madoola / Dead Zone &#124; SST-01|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230621105616/https://vgmdb.net/album/19610|archive-date=2023-06-21|url-status=live}}</ref> The game received a [[manga]] adaptation published as part of [[Tokuma Shoten]]'s ''Wanpaku Comic'' magazine on January 20, 1987, written and illustrated by Yū Minazuki.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Minazuki|first=Yū|title=マドゥーラの翼|magazine={{ill|Wanpaku Comic|lt=Wanpaku Comic|ja|わんぱっくコミック}}|series=Game Comic|volume=1|issue=31|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=January 20, 1987|pages=1–190|language=ja}}</ref> In February 1987, [[Shogakukan]] and Tokuma Shoten published their respective strategy guidebooks for the game.<ref>{{cite book|title=マドゥーラの翼 完全攻略法|series=ワンダーライフ|type=スペシャル|publisher=[[Shogakukan]]|date=February 9, 1987|pages=1–79|language=ja|isbn=978-4091041333}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=マドゥーラの翼|series=必勝完ペキ本|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=February 15, 1987|language=ja}}</ref> A second manga adaptation by the pseudonymous author "Ranmaru" was also published as part of ''Wanpaku Comic'' on February 25, 1987.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Ranmaru|url=https://archive.org/details/FamilyComputerTechnics20/page/n28/mode/1up|title=マドゥーラの翼|magazine={{ill|Wanpaku Comic|lt=Wanpaku Comic|ja|わんぱっくコミック}}|series=Technique Complete|volume=1|issue=36|edition=20|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=February 25, 1987|pages=29–52|language=ja}}</ref> A third manga adaptation was published as a double-pack with an adaptation of ''Ripple Island'' as part of ''Wanpaku Comic'' on February 20, 1988, authored by Kenji Mori.<ref name="GamingHelltwom"/><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Mori|first=Kenji|title=リップルアイランド|magazine={{ill|Wanpaku Comic|lt=Wanpaku Comic|ja|わんぱっくコミック}}|issue=55|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=February 20, 1988|pages=1–195|language=ja}}</ref>

''The Wing of Madoola'' received an album containing the original soundtrack and other Famicom titles, distributed in Japan by [[Scitron]] in 2004.<ref name="VGMdb2">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/408|title=FAMICOM 20TH ANNIVERSARY ORIGINAL SOUND TRACKS VOL.3 &#124; SCDC-00319|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221123022334/https://vgmdb.net/album/408|archive-date=2022-11-23|url-status=live}}</ref> The game's soundtrack was replicated along with the arranged track as part of a three-disc compilation album titled ''Rom Cassette Disc In Sunsoft'', distributed under City Connection's Clarice Disk label on June 29, 2011.<ref name="TWoMhg101"/><ref name="Cyzo">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyzo.com/2011/06/post_7751_entry.html|title=「とにかく既存のファミコンの音を壊したかった」影山雅司"音のサンソフト"を支えた男|work=Cyzo|date=June 29, 2011|access-date=2023-08-24|language=Japanese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160411164336/http://www.cyzo.com/2011/06/post_7751_entry.html|archive-date=2016-04-11|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="VGMdb3">{{cite web|url=http://vgmdb.net/album/26274|title=Rom Cassette Disc In SUNSOFT &#124; CDCD-10003|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221214073947/http://vgmdb.net/album/26274|archive-date=2022-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2011, another album containing the game's OST and other Sunsoft titles was released by [[Wave Master]].<ref name="VGMdb4">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/27926|title=SUNSOFT MUSIC COLLECTION Vol.1 &#124; WM-0661~3|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221214073947/https://vgmdb.net/album/27926|archive-date=2022-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref> That same year, a third album containing a new arrangement of the game's music was also released by City Connection.<ref name="VGMdb5">{{cite web|url=https://vgmdb.net/album/28973|title=Rom Cassette Disc In SUNSOFT Remix &#124; CDCD-10005|publisher=VGMdb|access-date=2023-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221214073947/https://vgmdb.net/album/28973|archive-date=2022-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 2021 and 2022, the manga adaptations by Mori and Minazuki were reissued by Tokuma Shoten as ebooks.<ref name="4Gamer.net1">{{cite web|author=Gueed|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20210812071/|title=懐かしの漫画雑誌「わんぱっくコミック」掲載作品が電子書籍で順次刊行へ。8月配信は"マドゥーラの翼""ファミコン突撃隊"などの5作品|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=August 12, 2021|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210813221448/https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20210812071/|archive-date=2021-08-13|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="4Gamer.net2">{{cite web|last=Sugiura|first=Ryo|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20220413064/|title=電子書籍「マドゥーラの翼・ゲームコミック版」が4月中旬に発売へ。気になる"ムフフな絵"の特典も付属|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=April 13, 2022|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220414153245/https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20220413064/|archive-date=2022-04-14|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="4Gamer.net3">{{cite web|author=Gueed|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20220415069/|title=「わんぱっくコミック・リバイバル」第II期スタート。"高機動戦隊メカ ヴォルガードII"（たまだとしみつ）など3作品を4月18日より配信|work=[[4Gamer.net]]|publisher=Aetas Inc.|date=April 15, 2022|access-date=2023-08-23|language=ja|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220415072829/https://www.4gamer.net/games/999/G999905/20220415069/|archive-date=2022-04-15|url-status=live}}</ref>

